@user I appreciate your research and your many posts of your learnings about $KAS. However, at the end of the day, Bitcoin is the perfect base layer for sound money. In time the L2s (like Lightning and others) will suffice for daily payment infrastructure, and users won’t have to also learn of another token + chain. I’m not concerned with decentralization of the Bitcoin L2s — things will be decentralized enough. In addition, I believe that eventually, L2s will be abstracted away, and users will simply use Bitcoin + Stablecoins in a single wallet. They won’t need to understand blockchain, base layers, L2s, etc etc. The experience will be much like the mobile banking apps of today. Bitcoin for savings, stablecoins for “checking.” But you won’t need permission to open an “account.” In conclusion, $KAS seems cool, but it’s not for me. Thank you for coming to my Ted talk. folded_hands

$BTC couldn’t spend even a few days post breakout without $Pump sucking 600million - and over a billion total out of the crypto community as everyone is sitting here cheering on their own demise. Most people didn’t get into the sale, and most tokens are in the hands of less than 300 people. If you missed the sale, you’re the chump at the table waiting for table scraps. You’ll still bite, and in all honestly, Pump probably runs way higher because of first mover advantage. It’s also only a billion dollar market cap at a hypothetical 25% circulating supply, and wouldn’t even put it in the top 50. Room to run. Here’s a scenario you DON’T want to see. An ICO craze sparked by this. It was too easy to take everyone’s money. People jumping all over each other to get into pre/public sales not understanding the effect until all of our money rests in the hands of a few. And that money isn’t coming back. It’s Sol eco Pumpfun launches 2.0, except worst, as you’re replacing Snipers with Pre-Sale insiders, and directly funding teams with $$. Even if you don’t participate in the chaos, you’ll get the negative downstream direct effects by watching your coins die. Another rotational environment that most can’t thrive in. I hope this doesn’t happen. I’m happy to get the hell out of the alt coin sector after 2025 as it’s a shark infested cesspool preying on the naive. KOLs don’t care about you. They have incentive to persuade you into unfavorable conditions that don’t benefit you. These people know exactly what they’re doing - and you’re walking into the arena thinking it’s a fair fight with your hands down about to lose everything you’ve got. Anyways, just some thoughts. Maybe this doesn’t spark a negative mania. Maybe we do attract a new batch of buyers who bring new money to the table, pumping all our coins as we ride BTC.D into the 40-50% levels, allowing newcomers to finally see what a real alt season looks like. Maybe there is way more participants and money sidelined than it seems. I’m not sure; but it’s important to be cognizant of all the moving parts around you right now. Don’t get liquidity sucked into the crypto hell pits of greed and despair. Don’t get caught holding backs in a rotational environment. Protect your hard earned money or it WILL get taken from you. AI Overview Stablecoin legislation, like the proposed GENIUS Act, is likely to benefit the Ethereum blockchain the most. This is because Ethereum is the primary blockchain for many of the largest stablecoins, such as USDC and USDT, and it provides the infrastructure for programmable tokens and smart contracts that are essential for stablecoin functionality. Here's why Ethereum benefits: Dominant Stablecoin Hosting:.Ethereum hosts a significant majority of the existing stablecoins, making it a central hub for this growing market. Programmable Tokens and Smart Contracts:.Ethereum's architecture allows for the creation of programmable tokens and the execution of smart contracts, which are crucial for stablecoin operations and their associated financial applications like lending and trading. Increased Adoption:.As stablecoin legislation fosters greater trust and wider adoption, it will drive increased transactions and activity on the Ethereum network, benefiting its overall ecosystem. Reduced Regulatory Uncertainty:.The legislation aims to clarify the regulatory landscape for stablecoins, which could reduce uncertainty and encourage more institutional participation, further boosting Ethereum's role. light_bulb Ethereum isn’t capped like Bitcoin’s 21M $BTC, but it’s not unlimited either. Originally, miners earned new ETH for creating blocks, but after upgrades, issuance was reduced. Now with Proof-of-Stake, validators stake ETH to secure the network and earn rewards — much smaller than before. On top of that, EIP-1559 burns a portion of transaction fees, permanently removing ETH from circulation. fire This means ETH supply grows slowly and can even become deflationary if network activity is high, making Ethereum scarce over time. coin rocket

Retracements in a bull market are healthy; going straight up isn’t...it’s an unattainable blow-off. October to February imo. A mix of green and red days is healthy. A stream of constant green pumps is just synthetic euphoria and usually signals you’re getting close to cycle FOMO tops.
